maml:description.maml:para: Pings things in a furiously fast fashion.
Uses .net ping and runspaces to ping a given network range very quickly. Optionally does a reverse lookup as well.

maml:Description.maml:para: Number of concurrent threads to use
Time to wait for ping response in milliseconds
Specify if reverse lookup is desired
Number of concurrent threads to use
Time to wait for ping response in milliseconds
Specify if reverse lookup is desired

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code:
PS C:\> Invoke-FuriousIp 10.88.64.0/29
Name State Hostname ---- ----- -------- 10.88.64.1 True 10.88.64.2 False 10.88.64.3 False 10.88.64.4 False 10.88.64.5 False 10.88.64.6 False

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 2 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code:
PS C:\> Invoke-FuriousIp 10.88.64.0/29 -ReverseLookup
Name State Hostname ---- ----- -------- 10.88.64.1 True core.example.com 10.88.64.2 False 10.88.64.3 False 10.88.64.4 False 10.88.64.5 False 10.88.64.6 False

dev:remarks.maml:para: Pings all address in 10.88.64.0/29 network and performs a reverse lookup for each.

maml:description.maml:para: CsLogger is a special runspace designed to receive logs and send them to a syslog server as fast as it can while the rest of your script gets on with it's job. Originally it was designed to circumvent a log server who's time precision only went as low as a second. This meant that logs that showed up out of order, with the same second in the timestamp, stayed out of order. Reading and sending these logs 1 second at a time fixed the issue. You can use DelayMilliseconds to customize this effect.

maml:Description.maml:para: Delay in Milliseconds between sending logs to SyslogServer
Delay in Milliseconds between sending logs to SyslogServer

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: >Start-CsLogger

dev:remarks.maml:para: Starts a CsLogger runspace with default delay of 1000 Milliseconds, $global:SyslogServer, and $global:SyslogPort settings.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: >Start-CsLogger -SyslogServer 'syslog.example.com' -SyslogPort 999 -DelayMilliseconds 5

dev:remarks.maml:para: Starts a CsLogger runspace with delay of 5 Milliseconds, sending logs to syslog.exampl.com over port 999.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: >Stop-CsLogger

maml:description.maml:para: Creates a customized Log Message based on the desired Verbosity level. Verbosity is set with the global variable $global:Verbosity. If the Write-CustomLog Verbosity Threshold is lower than $global:Verbosity, then Message will be written to the Verbose Stream and optionally to LogFile. LogFile defaults to $global:Logfile. The intended usage is to set Verbosity and LogFile at the top of whatever script you use this in.

maml:Description.maml:para: Changes the format of the LogMessage so it's easy to see the start of a section of logs
Changes the format of the LogMessage so it's easy to see the start of a section of logs

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> Write-CustomLog 1 "Special Log Message"

dev:remarks.maml:para: If $Global:Verbosity is higher than 1, write formatted log message to Verbose Stream. Also write to LogFile if set globally.

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 2 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> Write-CustomLog 1 "This is a Log header" -LogHeader

dev:remarks.maml:para: If $Global:Verbosity is higher than 1, write formatted log header message to Verbose Stream. Also write to LogFile if set globally.
